  "prompt": "When is India going to have plastic currency notes?",
  "response": "As of October 2023, India has not yet introduced plastic or polymer currency notes on a large scale. The Reserve Bank of India (RBI) has, however, conducted trials and introduced polymer-based notes in the past. For example, in 2014, the RBI issued a limited number of polymer \u20b910 notes in select cities as a pilot project to test their durability and security features.\n\nThe decision to transition to plastic currency notes depends on various factors, including cost-effectiveness, environmental impact, durability, and the ability to incorporate advanced security features. While polymer notes are known to last longer than paper notes and are more resistant to counterfeiting, India has not announced any immediate plans for a full-scale replacement of paper currency with polymer notes.\n\nThe RBI continues to explore innovations in currency technology, so it is possible that polymer notes could be introduced in the future, but there is no confirmed timeline for such a transition. For the most recent updates, it\u2019s best to monitor official announcements from the Reserve Bank of India.",
